	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New poultry sector policy pending in Ghana</h1>

			
			<h4>
												27 December 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to a report by USDA, the government of Ghana is preparing ‘a document on revitalizing the poultry industry in Ghana’. This follows sustained pressure from the National Poultry Farmers’ Association ‘to increase poultry tariffs to protect the industry’.</p><p>In October 2011, the Ghanaian Deputy Minister for Food and Agriculture, Dr Alfred Sugri Tia, committed the government to using ‘all legitimate means to discourage the importation of frozen meat in the country’. This commitment is to include support to local poultry farmers in securing cheaper feed, via support to the development of corn and soybean production. He also committed the government to the implementation of ‘both tariffs and non-tariff means to make their products competitive in the domestic market’.</p><p>In October, USDA reported delays experienced by Ghanaian poultry importers in securing import permits. However the Deputy Minister for Food and Agriculture indicated that the government ‘would not ban the importation of frozen meat as that would contravene the rules and conditions of international trade, but would rather create a congenial atmosphere for local farmers to capture the West African sub-regional market with comparatively low-price wholesome meat’.</p><p>Deputy Minister Tia noted that over the years Ghana had become ‘the dumping ground for imported chicken and beef’. This is borne out by the USDA analysis: in marketing year 2002, Ghana imported 20,752 tonnes of poultry parts, which by 2010 had risen to 98,000 tonnes, and 105,000 tonnes in 2011. This has contributed to reversing the rapid growth in the Ghanaian poultry sector which took place in the 1980 and 90s, when 80% of domestic chicken and egg needs were met from local production. By 2010, the market share of local producers was down to 10%, as ‘most of the small and medium-scale producers completely shut down’. USDA attributes this deteriorating performance to the ‘very high cost of production’ (feed, drugs and electricity), with imported poultry products being ‘30-40 percent cheaper than locally produced chicken’.</p><p>The strong growth of domestic consumption of poultry meat in urban areas shows a marked preference for imported frozen poultry products, which are pre-cut and ready to use. While the US dominated the Ghanaian poultry market 10 years ago, peaking at a 50% market share in 2003, by 2010 this market share had fallen to 22%, with Brazilian and EU frozen poultry meat exports gaining ground. Ghanaian consumers reportedly prefer Brazilian frozen poultry cuts, which are ‘perceived to be a better quality than the US type’. This is despite the price advantage held by US exporters (US poultry cuts are US$22 per 10-kg box, compared to US$24 for Brazilian and US$33 for EU poultry cuts).</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>USDA, ‘Ghana: Poultry and products brief annual’, <i>GAIN Report</i>, 7 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Poultry%20and%20Products%20Brief%20Annual_Accra_Ghana_10-7-2011.pdf" target="_self">http://gain.fas.usda.gov/Recent%20GAIN%20Publications/Poultry%20and%20Pr...</a></p><p><i>Thepoultrysite.com</i>, ‘Govt offers support to local meat producers’, 24 October 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23839/govt-offers-support-to-local-meat-producers" target="_self">http://www.thepoultrysite.com/poultrynews/23839/govt-offers-support-to-l...</a></p><p>FAO, <i>Food Outlook: Global market analysis</i>, November 2011 
<a href="http://www.fao.org/docrep/014/al981e/al981e00.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/docrep/014/al981e/al981e00.pdf</a></p><p><i>Barbados Advocate</i>, ‘Poultry producers must confront threats’, 8 November 2011</p><p>
<a href="http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=20816" target="_self">http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&amp;NewsID=20816</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>According to analysis from the Caribbean Poultry Association, changing policies in Russia and China (involving import restrictions or outright import bans, according to FAO) have seen ‘a huge accumulation of dark (chicken) meat’ in the US. This has left the US looking for alternative markets, not only ‘in its own backyard, the Caribbean’, but also in traditional markets such as Ghana.</p><p>Brazilian poultry meat exports, meanwhile, have reached a record level of 13.6 million tonnes, having increased 6% in 2010 and a further 5% in 2011 (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Poultry-Focus/Trends-in-Brazilian-and-Thai-poultry-exports-and-the-use-of-tariff-policy" target="_blank">Trends in Brazilian and Thai poultry exports and the use of tariff policy</a>’, 12 November 2011). EU exports are expected to increase 11.6% in 2011 and a further 2% in 2012, in a context where exports of ‘low-priced cuts and mechanically deboned meat to sub-Saharan Africa increased briskly’ (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Poultry/Poultry-Focus/EU-poultry-production-and-exports-continue-to-grow" target="_blank">EU poultry production and exports continue to grow</a>’, 12 November 2011).</p><p>This places the Ghanaian government in an extremely sensitive position in terms of the review of its poultry trade policy, given the commitment to not ban the importation of frozen poultry meat. In this context, some of the actions being sought by the Caribbean Poultry Association may be relevant. These include the strengthened use of SPS controls, including the introduction of prohibitions on the repackaging of frozen poultry meat products (imported poultry meat would need to be retailed in the original packaging in which it was imported) and a prohibition on the defrosting of frozen meat for sale as fresh poultry meat. The introduction of country-of-origin labelling is also under consideration.</p><p>These measures, however, are designed to complement tariff measures involving additional surcharges of up to 100%, which in the case of the Caribbean, remain within their WTO-bound tariff commitments.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
